
Experiment 3 
## **AIM**

Practice source code management on GitHub using the program written in Exercise-1.


---

## **OBJECTIVE**

To practice the following Git & GitHub operations:

* Adding files
* Committing changes
* Pushing to GitHub
* Pulling updates
* Creating branches
* Merging branches
* Collaborating with others



---

## **SOFTWARE REQUIREMENTS**

* Git installed
* GitHub account
* Code editor (VS Code recommended)



---

# ðŸš€ **PROCEDURE**

## **1. Configure Git (First Time Setup)**

```
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your-email@example.com"
git config --list
```



---

## **2. Create or Clone a Repository**

### **Option A â€“ Create a new repo on GitHub**

Then open it in VS Code.

### **Option B â€“ Clone an existing repo**

```
git clone https://github.com/your-username/your-repo-name.git
cd your-repo-name
```
---
## **3. Initialize a Local Repository (If not cloned)**
```
mkdir source-code-management
cd source-code-management
git init
```
---
## **4. Add Source Code Files**
```
echo "print('Hello DevOps')" > main.py
git status
git add main.py
```
---
## **5. Commit Changes**
```
git commit -m "Added main.py with Hello DevOps script"
```
---
## **6. Create and Manage Branches**
```
git branch feature-branch
git switch feature-branch
```
---
## **7. Modify Files and Commit**
```
echo "print('Feature work added')" >> main.py
git add main.py
git commit -m "Updated main.py in feature branch"
``-
---

## **8. Merge Feature Branch into Main**
```
git switch main
git merge feature-branch
```
---
## **9. Connect Local Repo to GitHub & Push Code**
```
git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/your-repo-name.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```
---
## **10. Pull Updates from GitHub**

```
git pull origin main
```
---
